<subSubSection id="88C065359B7EFFF8689929DA5436C123" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C06536BE9B7EFFF8689929DA565DC4A6" blockId="67.[189,303,989,1015]" box="[189,303,989,1015]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<heading id="9B2D81D29B7EFFF8689929DA565DC4A6" bold="true" box="[189,303,989,1015]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" reason="3">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF8689929DA565DC4A6" bold="true" box="[189,303,989,1015]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06536BE9B7EFFF868992E0C56A9C3E3" blockId="67.[189,1399,1035,1203]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF868992E0C56D2C374" authorityName="Lutken &amp; Mortensen" authorityYear="1889" box="[189,416,1035,1061]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="profundi">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF868992E0C56D2C374" box="[189,416,1035,1061]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Ophiactis profundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a hexamerous, fissiparous species. The disc diameter ranged from 
<quantity id="07229B5B9B7EFFF86D2D2E0B5221C377" box="[1289,1363,1036,1062]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
to 
<quantity id="07229B5B9B7EFFF868992E285673C318" box="[189,257,1071,1097]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
and all the specimens were found at one station on a deep-sea seamount in the South 
<collectingCountry id="B8CD762E9B7EFFF86CD32E28524FC318" box="[1271,1341,1071,1097]" name="China" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">China</collectingCountry>
Sea. Morphological descriptions of the 
<typeStatus id="1F61881C9B7EFFF86A752E5555CAC33D" box="[593,696,1106,1132]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF86AF92E555279C33D" authority="(Lutken &amp; Mortensen 1889)" baseAuthorityName="Lutken &amp; Mortensen" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[733,1291,1106,1132]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="profundi">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF86AF92E5554C8C33D" box="[733,954,1106,1132]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Ophiactis profundi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B7EFFF86BED2E555271C33D" author="Lutken C. F. &amp; Mortensen T." box="[969,1283,1106,1132]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" pagination="97 - 208" refId="ref38969" refString="Lutken C. F. &amp; Mortensen T. 1889. Reports on an exploration off the west coasts of Mexico, Central and Southern America and off the Galapagos Islands. XXV. The Ophiuridae. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 23 (2): 97 - 208." type="journal article" year="1889">Lütken &amp; Mortensen 1889</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the eastern Pacific Ocean and of other specimens from the Philippine Sea (
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B7EFFF86C272E7253C6C3DE" author="Koehler R." box="[1027,1204,1141,1167]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" pagination="1 - 480" refId="ref38296" refString="Koehler R. 1922 a. Ophiurans of the Philippine seas and adjacent waters. United States National Museum Bulletin 5 (100): 1 - 480." type="journal article" year="1922">Koehler 1922a</bibRefCitation>
) were similar to our specimens (
<figureCitation id="58E12A3B9B7EFFF869522E9F56BCC3E3" box="[374,462,1176,1202]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="68.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,441,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-107@68.[189,1398,440,1837]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="Fig. 38. Ophiactis profundi Lütken &amp; Mortensen, 1889 (IDSSE EEB-SW0017).A. Dorsal disc.B. Ventral disc. C. Radial shields. D. Oral frame. E. Dorsal arm. F. Ventral arm. G. Lateral arm. Abbreviations: ars = arm spine; as = adoral shield; dap = dorsal arm plate; gs = genital slit; os = oral shield; rs = radial shield; tp = tentacle pore; ts = tentacle scale; vap = ventral arm plate. Scale bars: A–B = 1 mm; C, G = 500 µm; D–F = 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6419615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6419615/files/figure.png" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06536BE9B7EFFF868992EDD5501C2F5" blockId="67.[189,1399,1242,1444]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
The dorsal arm plates are well-developed, widely triangular (
<figureCitation id="58E12A3B9B7EFFF86BAA2EDD548EC3A5" box="[910,1020,1242,1268]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="69.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-88@69.[189,1398,265,1872]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="Fig. 39. Ophiactis profundi Lütken &amp; Mortensen, 1889, SEM (IDSSE EEB-SW0017). A. Dorsal arm plate. B–C. Lateral arm plate (external, internal). D–G. Vertebrae. D. Proximal view. E. Distal view. F. Ventral view. G. Dorsal view. Abbreviations: D = dorsal; Dist = distal; dl = dorsal lobe; mo = muscle opening; no = nerve opening; Prox = proximal; V = ventral; vl = ventral lobe. Scale bars = 300 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6419617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6419617/files/figure.png" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Fig. 39A</figureCitation>
). The lateral arm plate has three well-developed arm spine articulations, formed by two subparallel bent lobes, not connected to each other, placed at an angle to the distal edge and equal in size, with two similar openings for muscle and nerve (
<figureCitation id="58E12A3B9B7EFFF8696D2F4456AEC20F" box="[329,476,1347,1374]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="69.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-88@69.[189,1398,265,1872]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="Fig. 39. Ophiactis profundi Lütken &amp; Mortensen, 1889, SEM (IDSSE EEB-SW0017). A. Dorsal arm plate. B–C. Lateral arm plate (external, internal). D–G. Vertebrae. D. Proximal view. E. Distal view. F. Ventral view. G. Dorsal view. Abbreviations: D = dorsal; Dist = distal; dl = dorsal lobe; mo = muscle opening; no = nerve opening; Prox = proximal; V = ventral; vl = ventral lobe. Scale bars = 300 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6419617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6419617/files/figure.png" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Fig. 39B–C</figureCitation>
). The vertebrae have a well-developed zygospondylous articulation, with a narrow, shallow dorsal furrow, not extending beyond the distal articulation, and the ambulacral groove is distalwards widened (
<figureCitation id="58E12A3B9B7EFFF869FD2F8D5515C2F5" box="[473,615,1418,1444]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="69.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-88@69.[189,1398,265,1872]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="Fig. 39. Ophiactis profundi Lütken &amp; Mortensen, 1889, SEM (IDSSE EEB-SW0017). A. Dorsal arm plate. B–C. Lateral arm plate (external, internal). D–G. Vertebrae. D. Proximal view. E. Distal view. F. Ventral view. G. Dorsal view. Abbreviations: D = dorsal; Dist = distal; dl = dorsal lobe; mo = muscle opening; no = nerve opening; Prox = proximal; V = ventral; vl = ventral lobe. Scale bars = 300 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6419617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6419617/files/figure.png" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Fig. 39D–F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06536BE9B7EFFF868992FCC5436C123" blockId="67.[189,1399,1483,1650]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF868992FCC56E8C2B4" baseAuthorityName="Lutken &amp; Mortensen" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[189,410,1483,1509]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="profundi">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF868992FCC56E8C2B4" box="[189,410,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Ophiactis profundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF86AA32FCC5371C2B4" authority="Lyman, 1879" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1879" box="[647,1027,1483,1510]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="flexuosa">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF86AA32FCC542DC2B4" box="[647,863,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Ophiactis flexuosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B7EFFF86B432FCB5371C2B4" author="Lyman T." box="[871,1027,1483,1510]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" pagination="17 - 83" refId="ref39129" refString="Lyman T. 1879. Ophiuridae and Astrophytidae of the &quot; Challenger &quot; expedition. Part II. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 6 (2): 17 - 83." type="journal article" year="1879">Lyman, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs in the shape of the oral shield and ventral arm plate, the shape of the oral papillae and the number of arms (
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF86CF22FE85229C159" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1879" box="[1238,1371,1518,1545]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="flexuosa">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF86CF22FE85399C158" box="[1238,1259,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF86CDF2FE95229C159" box="[1275,1371,1518,1544]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">flexuosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is pentamerous). 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF869482C155534C17D" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1879" box="[364,582,1554,1580]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="flexuosa">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF869482C155534C17D" box="[364,582,1554,1580]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Ophiactis flexuosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has distinct scales all around the radial shields (
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B7EFFF86C5A2C15578EC11E" author="Lutken C. F. &amp; Mortensen T." pageId="67" pageNumber="68" pagination="97 - 208" refId="ref38969" refString="Lutken C. F. &amp; Mortensen T. 1889. Reports on an exploration off the west coasts of Mexico, Central and Southern America and off the Galapagos Islands. XXV. The Ophiuridae. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 23 (2): 97 - 208." type="journal article" year="1889">Lütken &amp; Mortensen 1889</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF869362C325507C11E" authority="Lyman, 1869" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1869" box="[274,629,1589,1615]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="plana">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF869362C3256A2C11E" box="[274,464,1589,1615]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Ophiactis plana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B7EFFF869FC2C325507C11E" author="Lyman T." box="[472,629,1589,1615]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" pagination="309 - 354" refId="ref39022" refString="Lyman T. 1869. Preliminary report on the Ophiuridae and Astrophytidae dredged in deep water between Cuba and Florida Reef. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 1: 309 - 354." type="journal article" year="1869">Lyman, 1869</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is related to 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B7EFFF86B302C3254E9C11E" baseAuthorityName="Lutken &amp; Mortensen" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[788,923,1589,1615]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiactidae" genus="Ophiactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="profundi">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF86B302C3254E9C11E" box="[788,923,1589,1615]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">O. profundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs in the shape of the adoral shields and oral shield, and in the smaller oral papillae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="88C065359B7EFFF868992C9E532BC078" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C06536BE9B7EFFF868992C9E5624C1E2" blockId="67.[189,342,1689,1715]" box="[189,342,1689,1715]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<heading id="9B2D81D29B7EFFF868992C9E5624C1E2" bold="true" box="[189,342,1689,1715]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" reason="3">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B7EFFF868992C9E5624C1E2" bold="true" box="[189,342,1689,1715]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06536BE9B7EFFF868992CCF532BC078" blockId="67.[188,1399,1736,1833]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<quantity id="07229B5B9B7EFFF868992CCF5620C1B2" box="[189,338,1736,1763]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.375" metricValueMax="16.44" metricValueMin="2.31" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" unit="m" value="937.5" valueMax="1644.0" valueMin="231.0">231–1644 m</quantity>
. From the South 
<collectingCountry id="B8CD762E9B7EFFF86A332CCF552FC1B3" box="[535,605,1736,1762]" name="China" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">China</collectingCountry>
Sea recorded from the Lubang Islands near the 
<collectingCountry id="B8CD762E9B7EFFF86CA12CCF527BC1B3" box="[1157,1289,1736,1762]" name="Philippines" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Philippines</collectingCountry>
